  <li id="comment-36565" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://theedibleethic.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Leah</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/10/it-made-an-impression/#comment-36565"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-10-07T01:40:29-04:00">Monday, October 7, 2013 at 1:40 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>My first clafoutis was home made, out of the Mark Bittman &#8220;How to Cook Everything&#8221; book. It took two times as long to cook than suggested. I think this has to with the size of the dish you bake it in. If it&#39;s smaller and taller, it takes longer. Nevertheless, it was delicious. By now, I&#39;ve pretty much got his version memorized, because the proportions are all equal. I find it to be an impressive, yet easy dessert. People just eat the whole thing. Looking forward to trying yours out &#8212; love the idea of brown sugar, and pears are my favorite, although I&#39;ve never put them in clafoutis before. Personally, I love it hot &#8211; with the caramelized top, it&#39;s like eating a delicious dessert pancake.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
